I prefer we formulate this as:

```c
...
uint8_t t;
rc = pldm_msgbuf_extract(buf, t);
if (rc) {
    return rc;
}
if (t > PLDM_STR_TYPE_UTF_16BE) {
    return -EBADMSG;
}
req->image_set_ver.str_type = (enum pldm_firmware_update_string_type)t;
...
```

Also, as a bit of a nit, can we declare `t` at the top?

For consistency and to ward off any variable-length decodding issues, my preferred convention is that if we use an extracted value later in the parsing, we first test for error upon its extraction. That way we stay out of trouble with respect uninitialised values, but if it can be proved safe, the optimiser will elide the redundant check in the generated code.

So:

```
...
rc = pldm_msgbuf_extract(buf, pcomp->version.str_len);
if (rc) {
    return rc;
}
rc = pldm_msgbuf_extract_array(buf, pcomp.vesrion.str_len, pcomp->version.str_data, PLDM_FIRMWARE_MAX_STRING);
if (rc) {
    return rc;
}
...
```
